Vote Title: Motion to Waive CBA Re: Germaneness Re: Hirono Amdt. No. 20
Document Text: To protect the Medicare and Medicaid programs.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Flake Amdt. No. 52)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Flake Amdt. No. 52
Document Text: To strengthen Social Security and Medicare without raiding it to pay for new Government programs, like Obamacare, that have failed Americans by increasing premiums and reducing affordable health care options, to reform Medicaid without prioritizing able-bodied adults over the disabled, and to return regulation of insurance to State governments.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Sanders Amdt. No. 19)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Sanders Amdt. No. 19
Document Text: To prevent the Senate from breaking Donald Trump's promise that "there will be no cuts to Social Security, Medicare, and Medicaid".

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Nelson Amdt. No. 13)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Nelson Amdt. No. 13
Document Text: To create a point of order against legislation that would repeal health reforms that closed the prescription drug coverage gap under Medicare.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: King Amdt. No. 60)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: King Amdt. No. 60
Document Text: To create a point of order against legislation that would reduce health insurance access and affordability for individuals based on their occupation.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Barrasso Amdt. No. 173)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Barrasso Amdt. No. 173
Document Text: To establish a deficit-neutral reserve fund relating to rural health and repealing and replacing Obamacare.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Manchin Amdt. No. 64)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Manchin Amdt. No. 64
Document Text: To create a point of order against legislation that would harm rural hospitals and health care providers.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Heller Amdt. No. 167)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Heller Amdt. No. 167
Document Text: To establish a deficit-neutral reserve fund relating to strengthening Social Security and repealing Obamacare, which has increased health care costs, raised taxes on middle-class families, reduced access to high quality care, created disincentives for work, and caused tens of thousands of Americans to lose coverage they had and liked, and replacing it with patient-centered, step-by-step health reforms that provide access to quality, affordable private health care coverage for all American's and their families by increasing competition, State flexibility and individual choice, and safeguarding consumer protections that Americans support.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive the CBA Re: Baldwin Amdt. No. 81)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive the CBA Re: Baldwin Amdt. No. 81
Document Text: To create a point of order against legislation that makes young people sick again.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Flake Amdt. No. 176)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Flake Amdt. No. 176
Document Text: To establish a deficit-neutral reserve fund relating to enhancing health care and housing for veterans and their dependents by repealing Obamacare, facilitating medical facility leases, and prohibiting the Secretary of Veterans Affairs from employing individuals who have been convicted of a felony and medical personnel who have ever had their medical licenses or credentials revoked or suspended.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Tester Amdt. No. 104)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Tester Amdt. No. 104
Document Text: To create a point of order against legislation that would limit veterans' ability to choose VA health care.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Casey Amdt. No. 61)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Casey Amdt. No. 61
Document Text: To create a point of order against legislation that would make people with disabilities and chronic conditions sick again.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Barrasso Amdt. No. 181)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Barrasso Amdt. No. 181
Document Text: To establish a deficit-neutral reserve fund relating to strengthening Social Security and repealing and replacing Obamacare, which has increased health care costs, raised taxes on middle-class families, reduced access to high quality care, created disincentives for work, and caused tens of thousands of Americans to lose coverage they had and liked, and replacing Obamacare with patient-centered step-by-step health reforms that provide access to quality, affordable private health care coverage for all Americans and their families by increasing competition, State flexibility, and individual choice, and safe-guarding consumer protections, such as a ban on lifetime limits, that Americans support.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Hatch Amdt. No. 179)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Hatch Amdt. No. 179
Document Text: To establish a deficit-neutral reserve fund relating to reforming housing and Medicaid without prioritizing able-bodied adults over the disabled or raiding the Medicare Trust Funds to pay for new government programs, like Obamacare, which has failed Americans by increasing premiums and reducing affordable health care opportunities.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Menendez Amdt. No. 83)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Menendez Amdt. No. 83
Document Text: To create a point of order against legislation that would eliminate or reduce Federal funding to States under the Medicaid expansion.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Alexander Amdt. No. 174)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Alexander Amdt. No. 174
Document Text: To strengthen Social Security and Medicare without raiding them to pay for new government programs, like Obamacare, that have failed Americans by increasing premiums and reducing affordable health care options, to reform Medicaid without prioritizing able-bodied adults over the disabled, and to ensure that any importation does not increase risk to public health according to the Secretary of Health and Human Services.

Document Text: To establish a deficit-neutral reserve fund relating to lower prescription drug prices for Americans by importing drugs from Canada.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Wyden Amdt. No. 188)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Wyden Amdt. No. 188

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Fischer Amdt. No. 184)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Fischer Amdt. No. 184
Document Text: To establish a deficit-neutral reserve fund relating to strengthening Social Security or health care for women, which may include strengthening community health centers, and repealing and replacing Obamacare.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Gillibrand Amdt. No. 82)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Gillibrand Amdt. No. 82
Document Text: To create a point of order against legislation that makes women sick again.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Hatch Amdt. No. 180)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive All Applicable Budgetary Discipline Re: Hatch Amdt. No. 180
Document Text: To establish a deficit-neutral reserve fund relating to strengthening Social Security and repealing and replacing Obamacare, which has increased health care costs, raised taxes on middle-class families, reduced access to high quality care, created disincentives for work, and caused tens of thousands of Americans to lose coverage they had and liked, and replacing it with reforms that strengthen Medicaid, and the Children¿s Health Insurance Program without prioritizing able-bodied adults over the disabled or children and lead to patient-centered step-by-step health reforms that provide access to quality, affordable private health care coverage for all Americans and their families by increasing competition, State flexibility, and individual choice, and safe-guarding consumer protections that Americans support.

Question: On the Motion (Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Brown Amdt. No. 86)
Vote Title: Motion to Waive the C.B.A. Re: Brown Amdt. No. 86
Document Text: To create a point of order against legislation that would undermine the historic coverage gains the United States has made in children's health, which have resulted in the lowest uninsured rate for children in the Nation's history.
